International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Thu 5 Aug 2010
From: Akiko Kamata <Akiko.Kamata@fao.org> [edited]


FAO Animal Influenza Disease Emergency News [FAOAIDEnews], situation update 68
----------------------------------------------------------------------
At a glance: the latest HPAI outbreaks for the period 1 Jun-31 Jul 2010
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: AIDEnews publishes reports of confirmed HPAI cases using the
following sources: OIE, European Commission, FAO and national governments.
Africa
------
Egypt
-----
A total of 8 H5 HPAI positive cases were reported in 5 governorates
during 1-30 Jun 2010:
Dakahlia (1), Fayoum (2), Menoufia (1), Qalioubiya (1), and Sixth of
October (3) (The number of outbreaks in the governorate is in
brackets); 2 cases during 1-31 Jul 2010 in Qalioubiya (1) and Sixth
of October (1) Governorates. All of the outbreaks were in household
poultry, except for one commercial farm in the Dakahlia Governorate.

Asia
----
Bangladesh
----------
An H5N1 HPAI outbreak in Dhaka Division (Narayanganj District) was
reported on 19 Jun 2010.

Indonesia
---------
The Participatory Disease Surveillance & Response (PDSR) programme
through 33 Local Disease Control Centres covers 71 033 villages in 84
percent of Indonesia's 448 districts and municipalities in 29 of its
33 provinces. During May 2010, PDSR conducted surveillance in 1978
villages (2.8 percent). The overall HPAI incidence was 0.6 infected
villages per 1000 villages under surveillance. The disease incidence
did not vary very much as only a few provinces reported new infected
villages. The 4 provinces with the highest incidence values were
Yogyakarta (6.8 per 1000 villages), Sumatera Barat (2.2 per 1000
villages), Kalimantan Timur (1.7 per 1000 villages), and Lampung (1.6
per 1000 villages). The number of newly infected villages found
during May by island was: 14 in Sumatra, 29 in Java, and 2 in
Kalimantan. [On 3 Aug 2010, 2 affected villages were reportedly
recorded in South Sulawesi; see at
<http://birdflucorner.wordpress.com/2010/08/04/luwu-timur-south-sulawesi-thousands-of-bird-die-of-bird-flu/>.
Thanks to ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall for this
communication. - Mod.AS]

Viet Nam
--------
Outbreaks of H5N1 HPAI occurred in Quang Nam and Thai Nguyen
Provinces in June 2010 and Gia Lai Province in July 2010 and were
reported on the Government website. The last outbreak occurred on 18
Jul 2010 in chickens and Muscovy ducks in Ia Hrung Commune, Ia Grai
District of central Gia Lai Province.

Europe
------
Russian Federation
------------------
A total of 367 wild birds were found dead on 5 Jun 2010 on Ubsu-Nur
Lake, Republic of Tuva. The lake borders the northwestern Uvs
Province of Mongolia. Affected species included great crested grebe
(_Podiceps cristatus_), goosander (_Mergus merganser_), grey heron
(_Ardea cinerea_), gadwall (_Anas strepera_), and Eurasian spoonbill
(_Platalea leucorodia_). Samples tested positive for H5N1 by PCR.

--
Communicated by:
Juan Lubroth
Chief, Animal Health Service / CVO-FAO
Animal Production & Health Division
Food and Agriculture Organisation of the United Nations
<http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/home/en/index.htm>

[FAO's avian influenza maps (a 6-month map for the period 29 Jan-29
Jul 2010, and a 1-month map for the period 29 Jun-29 Jul 2010), are
available at <http://www.fao.org/avianflu/en/maps.html>.

The FAOAIDEnews situation update 68 of 5 Aug 2010 is available from
FAO's avian influenza website at
<http://www.fao.org/docrep/012/ak774e/ak774e00.pdf>. Among others, it
includes a useful table of all confirmed HPAI outbreaks in animals
and human cases/mortality since 2003, as of 31 Jul 2010. - Mod.AS]
